{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17519948","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17519948"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:17:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:17:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13107"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13107","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13107"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.14,0.26,0.52,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5544"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76420"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5544","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5544"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13107"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61917"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1934"},{"type":"tags","id":"2097"},{"type":"tags","id":"2778"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"8280"},{"type":"tags","id":"11010"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9448"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9842"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34435"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35731"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38405"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42848"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44388"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76420","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76420"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-week history of worsening numbness in his hands and feet, associated with poor balance and difficulty buttoning his shirt. He reports no pain, burning sensations, weakness, or clumsiness. His medical history includes active tuberculosis (diagnosed four months ago), hypertension, hypercholesterolaemia, atrial fibrillation, type 2 diabetes mellitus, and bipolar affective disorder. His medications include rifampicin, isoniazid, pyrazinamide, ethambutol, pyridoxine, perindopril, amlodipine, metformin, gliclazide, amiodarone, warfarin, and lithium. He drinks four cans of beer daily and has a 30 pack-year smoking history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Neurological examination reveals normal tone, power, and reflexes in all limbs. There is decreased sensation in a glove and stocking distribution with diminished vibration and proprioception bilaterally. His gait appears \u0027stamping\u0027 with dysdiadochokinesia.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Amiodarone toxicity","Lithium toxicity","Pyridoxine toxicity","Isoniazid toxicity","Metformin toxicity"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a symmetrical sensory neuropathy with preserved reflexes and motor function, which is characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003Epyridoxine toxicity\u003C/strong\u003E. Pyridoxine (Vitamin B6) supplements are given to patients on isoniazid to prevent deficiency, but excessive doses can cause toxicity. The classic presentation includes decreased sensation, vibration sense, and proprioception in a glove and stocking distribution with sensory ataxia. Symptoms typically improve within six months of withdrawing the supplement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIsoniazid toxicity\u003C/strong\u003E causes a painful peripheral sensory neuropathy with burning sensations and reduced pinprick sensation. This typically occurs after six months of treatment and is due to pyridoxine deficiency rather than excess.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmiodarone toxicity\u003C/strong\u003E causes a symmetrical sensorimotor neuropathy with decreased reflexes, which differs from this patient\u0027s pure sensory neuropathy with preserved reflexes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELithium toxicity\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes a symmetrical motor neuropathy with distal predominance, ranging from mild weakness to quadriplegia. The absence of motor symptoms makes this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetformin toxicity\u003C/strong\u003E can lead to vitamin B12 deficiency, causing a painful sensorimotor neuropathy with decreased reflexes and foot muscle atrophy. The absence of pain and preserved reflexes make this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pyridoxine toxicity causes a symmetrical peripheral sensory neuropathy with preserved reflexes and motor function","Drug-induced peripheral neuropathies can be distinguished by their specific pattern (sensory vs motor) and presence of pain","Patients on isoniazid require pyridoxine supplementation, but excessive doses can lead to toxicity"],"references":["Hemminger A, Wills BK. Vitamin B6 Toxicity.. In: StatPearls [Online]. [Updated 2023 Feb 7]. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK554500/","Hadtstein F, Vrolijk M. Vitamin B-6-induced neuropathy: exploring the mechanisms of pyridoxine toxicity. Advances in Nutrition. 2021 Sep;12(5):1911-29. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33912895/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61917"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13107"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61917","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61917"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-03T13:44:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-11T17:17:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5544"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76420"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end 